<section xml:id="review-graphing-lines">

    <title>Graphing Lines Chapter Review</title>

    <subsection>
        <title>Cartesian Coordinates</title>
        <p>In <xref ref="section-cartesian-coordinates">Section</xref> we covered the definition of the <xref ref="definition-cartesian-coordinate-system" text="title">Cartesian Coordinate System</xref> and how to plot points using the <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>-axes.</p>

        <!-- <paragraphs>
            <title>Cartesian Coordinate System</title>
            <p>The Cartesian coordinate system identifies the location of every point in a plane with an ordered pair. The first coordinate is the horizontal, <m>x</m>, distance and the second coordinate is the vertical, <m>y</m>, distance.</p>
        </paragraphs> -->

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>On paper, sketch a Cartesian coordinate system with units, and then plot the following points: <m>(3,2),(-5,-1),(0,-3),(4,0)</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <figure>
                    <caption>A Cartesian grid with the four points plotted.</caption>
                    <image>
                        <description>a Cartesian grid with four points plotted; the point (3,2) is 3 units to the right of the origin and two units up; the point (-5,-1) is 5 units to the left of the origin and 1 unit down; the point (0,-3) is on the y-axis 3 units down; the point (4,0) is right 4 units along the x-axis.</description>
                        <latex-image>
                            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                \begin{axis}[]
                                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(3, 2)} node[above] {$(3,2)$};
                                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-5, -1)} node[below] {$(-5,-1)$};
                                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0, -3)} node[right] {$(0,-3)$};
                                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(4, 0)} node[above] {$(4,0)$};
                                \end{axis}
                            \end{tikzpicture}]]>
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </solution>
        </example>
    </subsection>

    <subsection>
        <title>Graphing Equations</title>
        <p>In <xref ref="section-graphing-equations">Section</xref> we covered how to plot solutions to equations to produce a graph of the equation.</p>

            <!-- <p>To graph an equation with two variables <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>, we can choose some reasonable <m>x</m>-values, then calculate the corresponding <m>y</m>-values, and then plot the <m>(x,y)</m>-pairs as points. For many (not-so-complicated) algebraic equations, connecting those points with a smooth curve will produce an excellent graph.</p> -->
        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Graph the equation <m>y=-2x+5</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <figure>
                    <caption>Making a table for <m>y=-2x+5</m></caption>
                    <sidebyside margins="0%">
                        <table>
                        <caption>Set up the table</caption>
                        <tabular valign="top" bottom="minor">
                            <col halign="right" right="minor"/>
                            <col halign="right" right="minor"/>
                            <col halign="center"/>
                            <row bottom="medium">
                                <cell><m>x</m></cell>
                                <cell halign="center"><m>y=-2x+5</m></cell>
                                <cell>Point</cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell><m>-2</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>\phantom{-2(-2)+5=\substitute{9}}</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>\phantom{(-2,9)}</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell><m>-1</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>\phantom{-2(-1)+5=\substitute{7}}</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>\phantom{(-1,7)}</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell><m>0</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>\phantom{-2(0)+5=\substitute{5}}</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>\phantom{(0,5)}</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell><m>1</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>\phantom{-2(1)+5=\substitute{3}}</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>\phantom{(1,3)}</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row bottom="none">
                                <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>\phantom{-2(2)+5=\substitute{1}}</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>\phantom{(2,1)}</m></cell>
                            </row>
                        </tabular>
                    </table>
                    <table>
                        <caption>Complete the table</caption>
                        <tabular valign="top" bottom="minor">
                            <col halign="right" right="minor"/>
                            <col halign="right" right="minor"/>
                            <col halign="center"/>
                            <row bottom="medium">
                                <cell><m>x</m></cell>
                                <cell halign="center"><m>y=-2x+5</m></cell>
                                <cell>Point</cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell><m>-2</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>-2(-2)+5=\substitute{9}</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>(-2,9)</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell><m>-1</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>-2(-1)+5=\substitute{7}</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>(-1,7)</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell><m>0</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>-2(0)+5=\substitute{5}</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>(0,5)</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell><m>1</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>-2(1)+5=\substitute{3}</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>(1,3)</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row bottom="none">
                                <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>-2(2)+5=\substitute{1}</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>(2,1)</m></cell>
                            </row>
                        </tabular>
                        </table>
                    </sidebyside>
                </figure>

                <p>We use points from the table to graph the equation. First, plot each point carefully. Then, connect the points with a smooth curve. Here, the curve is a straight line. Lastly, we can communicate that the graph extends further by sketching arrows on both ends of the line.</p>

                <figure>
                    <caption>Graphing the Equation <m>y=-2x+5</m></caption>
                    <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
                        <figure>
                        <caption>Use points from the table</caption>
                        <image>
                            <description>a Cartesian grid with points (-2,9),(-1,7),(0,5),(1,3),(2,1)</description>
                            <latex-image>
                                <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                    \begin{axis}[ymin=-1,ymax=10,
                                                xtick=,
                                                minor xtick=,
                                                ytick=,
                                                minor ytick=,]
                                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-2,9)} node[left,rotate=30]{$(-2,9)$};
                                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-1,7)} node[left,rotate=30]{$(-1,7)$};
                                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0,5)} node[left,rotate=30]{$(0,5)$};
                                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(1,3)} node[left,rotate=30]{$(1,3)$};;
                                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(2,1)} node[left,rotate=30]{$(2,1)$};;
                                    \end{axis}
                                \end{tikzpicture}
                                ]]>
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                    </figure>
                    <figure>
                        <caption>Connect the points in whatever pattern is apparent</caption>
                        <image>
                            <description>a Cartesian grid with points (-2,9),(-1,7),(0,5),(1,3),(2,1);they are connected with a solid line with arrows on each end</description>
                            <latex-image>
                                <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                    \begin{axis}[ymin=-1,ymax=10,
                                                xtick=,
                                                minor xtick=,
                                                ytick=,
                                                minor ytick=,]
                                        \addplot+[domain=-2.5:3] {-2*x+5};
                                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-2,9)} node[left,rotate=30]{$(-2,9)$};
                                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-1,7)} node[left,rotate=30]{$(-1,7)$};
                                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0,5)} node[left,rotate=30]{$(0,5)$};
                                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(1,3)} node[left,rotate=30]{$(1,3)$};;
                                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(2,1)} node[left,rotate=30]{$(2,1)$};;
                                    \end{axis}
                                \end{tikzpicture}
                                ]]>
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                        </figure>
                    </sidebyside>
                </figure>
            </solution>
        </example>
    </subsection>

    <subsection>
        <title>Exploring Two-Variable Data and Rate of Change</title>
        <p>In <xref ref="section-exploring-two-variable-data-and-rate-of-change">Section</xref> we covered how to find patterns in tables of data and how to calculate the <xref ref="definition-rate-of-change" text="title">rate of change</xref> between points in data.</p>

        <paragraphs>
            <title>Exploring Two-Variable Data and Rate of Change</title>
            <p>For a linear relationship, by its data in a table, we can see the rate of change (slope) and the line's <m>y</m>-intercept, thus writing the equation.</p>
        </paragraphs>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <sidebyside>
                    <p>Write an equation in the form <m>y=\ldots</m> suggested by the pattern in the table.</p>
                    <table>
                        <caption>A table of linear data.</caption>
                        <tabular>
                            <row bottom="medium">
                                <cell><m>x</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>y</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell><m>0</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>-4</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell><m>1</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>-6</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>-8</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell><m>3</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>-10</m></cell>
                            </row>
                        </tabular>
                    </table>
                </sidebyside>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <sidebyside>
                    <p>We consider how the values change from one row to the next. From row to row, the <m>x</m>-value increases by <m>1</m>. Also, the <m>y</m>-value decreases by <m>2</m> from row to row.</p>

                    <tabular >
                        <row bottom="medium">
                            <cell />
                            <cell><m>x</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>y</m></cell>
                            <cell />
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell />
                            <cell><m>0</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>-4</m></cell>
                            <cell />
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>{}+1\rightarrow</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>1</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>-6</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>\leftarrow{}-2</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>{}+1\rightarrow</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>-8</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>\leftarrow{}-2</m></cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><m>{}+1\rightarrow</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>3</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>-10</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>\leftarrow{}-2</m></cell>
                        </row>
                    </tabular>
                </sidebyside>

                <p>Since row-to-row change is always <m>1</m> for <m>x</m> and is always <m>-2</m> for <m>y</m>, the rate of change from one row to another row is always the same: <m>-2</m> units of <m>y</m> for every <m>1</m> unit of <m>x</m>.</p>

                <p>We know that the output for <m>x = 0</m> is <m>y = -4</m>. And our observation about the constant rate of change tells us that if we increase the input by <m>x</m> units from <m>0</m>, the ouput should decrease by <m>\overbrace{(-2)+(-2)+\cdots+(-2)}^{x\text{ times}}</m>, which is <m>-2x</m>. So the output would be <m>-4-2x</m>.</p>

                <p>So the equation is <m>y=-2x-4</m>.</p>
            </solution>
        </example>
    </subsection>

    <subsection>
        <title>Slope</title><idx><h>slope</h><h>review</h></idx>
        <p>In <xref ref="section-slope">Section</xref> we covered the definition of <xref ref="definition-slope">slope</xref> and how to use slope-triangles to calculate slope. There is also the <xref ref="equation-slope-formula" text="title">slope formula</xref> which helps find the slope through any two points.</p>

            <!-- <p>When <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> are two variables where the rate of change between any two points is always the same, we call this common rate of change the <term>slope</term>. Since having a constant rate of change means the graph will be a straight line, it's also called the <term>slope of the line</term>.</p>

            <p>We can find a line's slope by drawing a slope-triangle on the line's graph, and then using the formula<men>m=\frac{\text{change in $y$}}{\text{change in $x$}}=\frac{\Delta y}{\Delta x}</men></p> -->

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Find the slope of the line in the following graph.</p>
                <figure>
                    <caption>The line with two points indicated.</caption>
                    <image width="47%">
                        <description>This is a grid with a line, passing the points (3,15) and (6,27).</description>
                        <latex-image>
                        <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                            \begin{axis}[xlabel={x},
                                        ylabel={y},
                                        xmin=-2,xmax=8,
                                        ymin=-5,ymax=30,
                                        minor ytick=,
                                        minor xtick=,
                                        xtick={2,4,6},
                                        ytick={5,10,...,25},
                                        clip=false]
                                \addplot+[domain = -2:6.75]{4*x+3};
                                \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(3, 15)} node[above left] {$(3,15)$};
                                \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(6, 27)} node[above left] {$(6,27)$};
                            \end{axis}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                        ]]>
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
                    <figure>
                        <caption>The line with a slope triangle drawn.</caption>
                        <image>
                        <description>This is a grid with a line, passing the points (3,15) and (6,27). A slope triangle is drawn, starting at (3,15), passing (6,15), and ends at (6,27). The label from (3,15) to (6,15) is "6-3=3"; the label from (6,15) to (6,27) is "27-15=12".</description>
                        <latex-image>
                        <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                            \begin{axis}[xlabel={x},
                                        ylabel={y},
                                        xmin=-2,xmax=8,
                                        ymin=-5,ymax=30,
                                        minor ytick=,
                                        minor xtick=,
                                        xtick={2,4,6},
                                        ytick={5,10,...,25},
                                        clip=false]
                                \addplot+[domain = -2:6.75]{4*x+3};
                                \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(3, 15)} node[above left] {$(3,15)$};
                                \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(6, 27)} node[above left] {$(6,27)$};
                                \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(3,15) (6,15)} node[pos=0.5,below,align=left] {$6-3$\\${}=3$};
                                \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(6,15) (6,27)} node[pos=0.5,below,rotate=90,align=left] {$27-15$\\${}=12$};
                            \end{axis}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                        ]]>
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                    </figure>
                    <p>We picked two points on the line, and then drew a slope triangle. Next, we will do:<me>\text{slope}=\frac{12}{3}=4</me>The line's slope is <m>4</m>.</p>
                </sidebyside>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <example>
            <title>Finding a Line's Slope by the Slope Formula</title>
            <statement>
                <p>Use the <xref ref="equation-slope-formula" text="title">slope formula</xref> to find the slope of the line that passes through the points <m>(-5,25)</m> and <m>(4,-2)</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\text{slope}\amp=\frac{y_2-y_1}{x_2-x_1}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=\frac{-2-(25)}{4-(-5)}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=\frac{-27}{9}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp=-3</mrow>
                    </md>
                The line's slope is <m>-3</m>.</p>
            </solution>
        </example>
    </subsection>

    <subsection>
        <title>Slope-Intercept Form</title>
        <p>In <xref ref="section-slope-intercept-form">Section</xref> we covered the definition of <xref ref="definition-point-slope-form" text="title">slope intercept-form</xref> and both wrote equations in slope-intercept form and graphed lines given in slope-intercept form.</p>

        <!-- <paragraphs>
            <title>Graphing a Line in Slope-Intercept Form</title>
            <p>A line's equation in slope-intercept form looks like <m>y=mx+b</m>, where <m>m</m> is the line's slope, and <m>b</m> is the <m>y</m> value of the line's <m>y</m>-intercept.</p>
            <p>We can use a line's <m>y</m>-intercept and slope triangles to graph it.</p>
        </paragraphs> -->
        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Graph the line <m>y=-\frac{5}{2}x+4</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <figure>
                    <caption>Graphing <m>y=-\frac{5}{2}x+4</m></caption>
                    <sidebyside widths="32% 32% 32%" margins="0%">
                    <figure>
                        <caption>First, plot the line's <m>y</m>-intercept, <m>(0,4)</m>.</caption>
                        <image>
                            <description>a Cartesian grid with the point (0,4) plotted</description>
                            <latex-image>
                            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                    \begin{axis}[ymin=-10,ymax=10,
                                                ytick={-8,-6,...,8},
                                                minor ytick={-9,-8,...,9},
                                                ]
                                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0,4)} node[above right] {$(0,4)$};
                                    \end{axis}
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                            ]]>
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                    </figure>
                    <figure>
                        <caption>The slope is <m>-\frac{5}{2}=\frac{-5}{2}=\frac{5}{-2}</m>. So we can try using a <q>run</q> of <m>2</m> and a <q>rise</q> of <m>-5</m> or a <q>run</q> of <m>-2</m> and a <q>rise</q> of <m>5</m>.</caption>
                        <image>
                            <description>the previous plot of the y-intercept with slope triangles drawn; they go right 2 and down 5 twice to the right; from the y-intercept they also go up 5 and left 2 once; the points plotted are (-2,9), (0,4), (2,-1), (4,-6)</description>
                            <latex-image>
                            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                    \begin{axis}[ymin=-10,ymax=10,
                                                ytick={-8,-6,...,8},
                                                minor ytick={-9,-8,...,9},
                                                ]
                                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0,4)};
                                        \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(0,4) (2,4) (2,-1)};
                                        \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(2,-1) (4,-1) (4,-6)};
                                        \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(0,4) (-2,4) (-2,9)};
                                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-2,9)} node[below left] {$(2,-9)$};
                                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(2,-1)} node[below left] {$(2,-1)$};
                                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(4,-6)} node[above right] {$(4,-6)$};
                                    \end{axis}
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                            ]]>
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                    </figure>
                    <figure>
                        <caption>Arrowheads and labels are encouraged.</caption>
                        <image>
                            <description>the previous plot with a solid line drawn through all of the points; there are arrowheads on each end of the line</description>
                            <latex-image>
                            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                    \begin{axis}[ymin=-10,ymax=10,
                                                ytick={-8,-6,...,8},
                                                minor ytick={-9,-8,...,9},
                                                ]
                                        \addplot+[domain=-2.4:5.6] {-5/2*x+4} node[pos=0.6,sloped,above] {$y=-\frac{5}{2}x+4$};
                                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-2,9)};
                                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0,4)};
                                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(2,-1)};
                                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(4,-6)};
                                    \end{axis}
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                            ]]>
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                    </figure>
                    </sidebyside>
                </figure>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <paragraphs>
            <title>Writing a Line's Equation in Slope-Intercept Form Based on Graph</title>

            <p>Given a line's graph, we can identify its <m>y</m>-intercept, and then find its slope by a slope triangle. With a line's slope and <m>y</m>-intercept, we can write its equation in the form of <m>y=mx+b</m>.</p>
        </paragraphs>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
                    <p>Find the equation of the line in the graph.</p>
                    <figure>
                        <caption>Graph of a line</caption>
                        <image>
                            <description>a coordinate graph of a line;three points on the line are (-3,12),(0,10) and (3,8)</description>
                            <latex-image>
                            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                    \begin{axis}[ymin=-2,ymax=16,
                                                ytick={2,4,...,14},
                                                minor ytick={-2,-1,...,16},
                                                ]
                                        \addplot+[domain=-7:7] {-2/3*x+10};
                                    \end{axis}
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                            ]]>
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                    </figure>
                </sidebyside>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
                    <figure>
                        <caption>Identify the line's <m>y</m>-intercept, <m>10</m>.</caption>
                        <image>
                            <description>the previous graph showing the line crosses the y-axis at 10 or (0,10)</description>
                            <latex-image>
                            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                    \begin{axis}[ymin=-2,ymax=16,
                                                ytick={2,4,...,14},
                                                minor ytick={-2,-1,...,16},
                                                ]
                                        \addplot+[domain=-7:7] {-2/3*x+10};
                                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0,10)} node[right] {$(0,10)$};
                                    \end{axis}
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                            ]]>
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                    </figure>
                    <figure>
                        <caption>Identify the line's slope by a slope triangle. Note that we can pick any two points on the line to create a slope triangle. We would get the same slope: <m>-\frac{2}{3}</m></caption>
                        <image>
                            <description>the previous graph with slope triangles drawn moving right 3 units and down two units</description>
                            <latex-image>
                            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                    \begin{axis}[ymin=0,ymax=20,
                                                ytick={0,5,15,20},
                                                y axis line style = {->},
                                                minor ytick={0,1,...,20}]
                                        \addplot+[domain=-7:7] {-2/3*x+10};
                                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0,10)};
                                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(3,8)} node[below] {$(3,8)$};
                                        \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-3,12)} node[above] {$(-3,12)$};
                                        \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(0,10) (3,10)} node[pos=0.5,above,align=center] {$3$};
                                        \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(3,10) (3,8)} node[pos=0.5,right,align=center] {$-2$};
                                        \addplot[guideline,->] coordinates {(-3,10) (0,10)} node[pos=0.5,below,align=center] {$3$};
                                        \addplot[guideline] coordinates {(-3,10) (-3,12)} node[pos=0.5,left,align=center] {$-2$};
                                    \end{axis}
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                            ]]>
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                    </figure>
                </sidebyside>
                <p>With the line's slope <m>-\frac{2}{3}</m> and <m>y</m>-intercept <m>10</m>, we can write the line's equation in slope-intercept form: <m>y=-\frac{2}{3}x+10</m>.</p>
            </solution>
        </example>
    </subsection>

    <subsection>
        <title>Point-Slope Form</title>
        <p>In <xref ref="section-point-slope-form">Section</xref> we covered the definition of <xref ref="definition-point-slope-form" text="title">point-slope form</xref> and both wrote equations in point-slope form and graphed lines given in point-slope form.</p>

            <!-- <p>A line's point-slope form equation is in the form of <m>y=m\left(x-x_0\right)+y_0</m>, where <m>m</m> is the line's slope, and <m>(x_0,y_0)</m> is a point on the line.</p> -->
        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>A line passes through <m>(-6,0)</m> and <m>(9,-10)\text{.}</m> Find this line's equation in point-slope<!--  and slope-intercept form -->.</p>
            </statement>

            <solution>
                <p>We will use the <xref ref="equation-slope-formula" text="title">slope formula</xref> to find the slope first. After labeling those two points as <m>(\overset{x_1}{-6},\overset{y_1}{0}) \text{ and } (\overset{x_2}{9},\overset{y_2}{-10})\text{,}</m> we have:<md>
                    <mrow>\text{slope}\amp=\frac{y_2-y_1}{x_2-x_1}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=\frac{-10-0}{9-(-6)}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=\frac{-10}{15}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=-\frac{2}{3}</mrow>
                </md></p>

                <p>Now the point-slope equation looks like <m>y=-\frac{2}{3}(x-x_0)+y_0\text{.}</m> Next, we will use <m>(9,-10)</m> and substitute <m>x_0</m> with <m>9</m> and <m>y_0</m> with <m>-10\text{,}</m> and we have:<md>
                    <mrow>y\amp=-\frac{2}{3}(x-x_0)+y_0</mrow>
                    <mrow>y\amp=-\frac{2}{3}(x-9)+(-10)</mrow>
                    <mrow>y\amp=-\frac{2}{3}(x-9)-10</mrow>
                </md></p>
<!--
                <p>Next, we will change the point-slope equation into slope-intercept form:<md>
                        <mrow>y\amp=-\frac{2}{3}(x-9)-10</mrow>
                        <mrow>y\amp=-\frac{2}{3}x+6-10</mrow>
                        <mrow>y\amp=-\frac{2}{3}x-4</mrow>
                </md></p> -->
            </solution>
        </example>
    </subsection>



    <subsection>
        <title>Standard Form</title>
        <p>In <xref ref="section-standard-form">Section</xref> we covered the definition of <xref ref="definition-standard-form" text="title">standard form</xref> of a linear equation. We converted equations from standard form to slope-intercept form and vice versa. We also graphed lines from standard form by finding the intercepts of the line.</p>

            <!-- <p>A line's equation in standard form looks like <m>Ax+By=C</m>. We need to convert a line's equation from standard form to slope-intercept form, and vice versa.</p> -->

            <example>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        <ol label="a.">
                            <li><p>Convert <m>2x+3y=6</m> into slope-intercept form.</p></li>
                            <li><p>Convert <m>y=-\frac{4}{7}x-3</m> into standard form.</p></li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p><ol label="a.">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>2x+3y\amp=6</mrow>
                                    <mrow>2x+3y\subtractright{2x}\amp=6\subtractright{2x}</mrow>
                                    <mrow>3y\amp=-2x+6</mrow>
                                    <mrow>\divideunder{3y}{3}\amp=\divideunder{-2x+6}{3}</mrow>
                                    <mrow>y\amp=\frac{-2x}{3}+\frac{6}{3}</mrow>
                                    <mrow>y\amp=-\frac{2}{3}x+2</mrow>
                                </md>
                            The line's equation in slope-intercept form is <m>y=-\frac{2}{3}x+2</m>.</p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>y\amp=-\frac{4}{7}x-3</mrow>
                                    <mrow>\multiplyleft{7}y\amp=\multiplyleft{7}(-\frac{4}{7}x-3)</mrow>
                                    <mrow>7y\amp=7\cdot(-\frac{4}{7}x)-7\cdot3</mrow>
                                    <mrow>7y\amp=-4x-21</mrow>
                                    <mrow>7y\addright{4x}\amp=-4x-21\addright{4x}</mrow>
                                    <mrow>4x+7y\amp=-21</mrow>
                                </md>The line's equation in standard form is <m>4x+7y=-21</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol></p>
                </solution>
            </example>

        <p>To graph a line in standard form, we could first change it to slope-intercept form, and then graph the line by its <m>y</m>-intercept and slope triangles. A second method is to graph the line by its <m>x</m>-intercept and <m>y</m>-intercept.</p>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Graph <m>2x-3y=-6</m> using its intercepts. And then use the intercepts to calculate the line's slope.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>We calculate the line's <m>x</m>-intercept by substituting <m>y=0</m> into the equation<md>
                    <mrow>2x-3y\amp=-6</mrow>
                    <mrow>2x-3(\substitute{0})\amp=-6</mrow>
                    <mrow>2x\amp=-6</mrow>
                    <mrow>x\amp=-3</mrow>
                </md>So the line's <m>x</m>-intercept is <m>(-3,0)\text{.}</m></p>

                <p>Similarly, we substitute <m>x=0</m> into the equation to calculate the <m>y</m>-intercept:<md>
                    <mrow>2x-3y\amp=-6</mrow>
                    <mrow>2(\substitute{0})-3y\amp=-6</mrow>
                    <mrow>-3y\amp=-6</mrow>
                    <mrow>y\amp=2</mrow>
                </md>So the line's <m>y</m>-intercept is <m>(0,2)</m>.</p>

                <p>With both intercepts' coordinates, we can graph the line:</p>

                <figure>
                    <caption>Graph of <m>2x-3y=-6</m></caption>
                        <image width="47%">
                        <description>the graph of line 2x-3y=-6 with the x-intercept plotted at (-3,0) and the y-intercept at (0,2).</description>
                            <latex-image>
                                <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                    \begin{axis}[xmin=-5,xmax=2,
                                        ymin=-1,ymax=4,
                                        minor xtick=,
                                        minor ytick=,
                                        xtick={-4,-3,...,1},
                                        ytick={1,2,3}]
                                    \addplot+[domain=-4.5:2]{2/3*x+2};
                                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0, 2)} node[above left] {$(0,2)$};;
                                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-3, 0)} node[above left] {$(-3,0)$};
                                \end{axis}
                            \end{tikzpicture}]]>
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>

                <p>Now that we have graphed the line we can read the slope. The rise is 2 units and the run is 3 units so the slope is <m>\frac{2}{3}</m>.</p>

            </solution>
        </example>
    </subsection>

    <subsection>
        <title>Horizontal, Vertical, Parallel, and Perpendicular Lines</title>
        <p>In <xref ref="section-horizontal-vertical-parallel-and-perpendicular-lines">Section</xref> we covered what equations of horizontal and vertical lines. We also covered the relationships between the slopes of <xref ref="fact-parallel-lines" text="title">parallel</xref> and <xref ref="fact-perpendicular-lines" text="title">perpendicular</xref> lines.</p>

        <!-- <paragraphs>
