        <!-- <paragraphs>
            <title>Parallel and Perpendicular Lines</title>
            <p>Two lines are parallel if and only if they have the same slope.</p> -->
            <example>
                <statement>
                    <p>Line <m>m</m>'s equation is <m>y=-2x+20</m>. Line <m>n</m> is parallel to <m>m</m>, and line <m>n</m> also passes the point <m>(4,-3)</m>. Find an equation for line <m>n</m> in point-slope form.</p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>Since parallel lines have the same slope, line <m>n</m>'s slope is also <m>-2</m>. Since line <m>n</m> also passes the point <m>(4,-3)</m>, we can write line <m>n</m>'s equation in point-slope form:
                        <md>
                            <mrow>y\amp=m(x-x_1)+y_1</mrow>
                            <mrow>y\amp=-2(x-4)+(-3)</mrow>
                            <mrow>y\amp=-2(x-4)-3</mrow>
                        </md>
                    <!-- We can also easily get the line's equation in slope-intercept form:
                        <md>
                            <mrow>y\amp=-2(x-4)-3</mrow>
                            <mrow>y\amp=-2x+8-3</mrow>
                            <mrow>y\amp=-2x+5</mrow>
                        </md> -->
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </example>

            <p>Two lines are perpendicular if and only if the product of their slopes is <m>-1</m>.</p>
            <example>
                <statement>
                    <p>Line <m>m</m>'s equation is <m>y=-2x+20</m>. Line <m>n</m> is perpendicular to <m>m</m>, and line <m>q</m> also passes the point <m>(4,-3)</m>. Find an equation for line <m>q</m> in slope-intercept form.</p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>Since line <m>m</m> and <m>q</m> are perpendicular, the product of their slopes is <m>-1</m>. Because line <m>m</m>'s slope is given as <m>-2</m>, we can find line <m>q</m>'s slope is <m>\frac{1}{2}</m>.</p>
                    <p>Since line <m>q</m> also passes the point <m>(4,-3)</m>, we can write line <m>q</m>'s equation in point-slope form:
                        <md>
                            <mrow>y\amp=m(x-x_1)+y_1</mrow>
                            <mrow>y\amp=\frac{1}{2}(x-4)+(-3)</mrow>
                            <mrow>y\amp=\frac{1}{2}(x-4)-3</mrow>
                        </md>
                    We can now convert this equation to slope-intercept form:
                        <md>
                            <mrow>y\amp=\frac{1}{2}(x-4)-3</mrow>
                            <mrow>y\amp=\frac{1}{2}x-2-3</mrow>
                            <mrow>y\amp=\frac{1}{2}x-5</mrow>
                        </md>
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </example>
        <!-- </paragraphs> -->
    </subsection>

    <subsection>
        <title>Linear Inequalities in Two Variables</title>
        <p>In <xref ref="section-linear-inequalities-in-two-variables">Section</xref> we covered how to graph the solution set for an inequality with two variables as a region in the plane.</p>

            <!-- <p>When we graph lines like <m>y=2x+1</m>, we are graphing points which satisfy the relationship <m>y=2x+1</m>, like <m>(0,1), (1,3), (2,5)</m>, etc. Similarly, we can graph linear inequalities like <m>y\gt2x+1</m> by plotting all points which satisfies the inequality, like <m>(0,2), (0,3), (1,4), (1,5)</m>, etc. All these points form a region, instead of a line.</p> -->

            <example>
                <statement>
                    <p>Graph <m>y\gt2x+1\text{.}</m></p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>There are two steps to graph an inequality.<ol>
                    <li>Graph the line <m>y=2x+1\text{.}</m> Because the inequality symbol is <m>\gt\text{,}</m> (instead of <m>\ge</m>) the line should be dashed (instead of solid).</li>
                    <li>Next, we need to decide whether to shade the region above <m>y=2x+1</m> or below it. We will choose a point to test whether <m>y\gt2x+1</m> is true. As long as the line doesn't cross <m>(0,0)\text{,}</m> we will use <m>(0,0)</m> to test, because the number <m>0</m> is the easiest number for calculation.<md>
                        <mrow>y\gt2x+1</mrow>
                        <mrow>0\stackrel{?}{\gt}2(0)+1</mrow>
                        <mrow>0\stackrel{\text{no}}{\gt}1</mrow>
                    </md>Because <m>0\gt1</m> is not true, the point <m>(0,0)</m> is not a solution and should not be shaded. As a result, we shade the region without <m>(0,0)\text{.}</m>
                    </li></ol>
                    </p>

                <sidebyside widths="45% 45%">
                    <figure>
                        <caption>Step 1 of graphing <m>y\gt2x+1</m></caption>
                        <image>
                        <description>a coordinate plane with y=2x+1 graphed as a dashed line</description>
                        <latex-image>
                        <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                \begin{axis}[
                                    xmin=-5,xmax=5,ymin=-5,ymax=5,
                                    minor xtick=, minor ytick=,
                                    xtick={-4,-3,...,4},ytick={-4,-3,...,4}
                                    ]
                                    \addplot[domain=-3:2,secondarycurve,dashed] {2*x+1};
                                \end{axis}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                        ]]>
                        </latex-image>
                        </image>
                    </figure>

                    <figure>
                        <caption>Step 2 of graphing <m>y\gt2x+1</m></caption>
                        <image>
                        <description>the previous graph with the region above the line shaded</description>
                        <latex-image>
                        <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                \begin{axis}[
                                    xmin=-5,xmax=5,ymin=-5,ymax=5,
                                    minor xtick=, minor ytick=,
                                    xtick={-4,-3,...,4},ytick={-4,-3,...,4}
                                    ]
                                    \addplot[domain=-3:2,secondarycurve,dashed] {2*x+1};
                                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0,0)} node[above right] {test point: $(0,0)$};
                                    \fill[blue, opacity=0.4] (axis cs:-5,-5) -- (axis cs:-3,-5) -- (axis cs:2,5) -- (axis cs:-5,5) -- cycle;
                                \end{axis}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                        ]]>
                        </latex-image>
                        </image>
                    </figure>
                </sidebyside>
                </solution>
            </example>
    </subsection>

